  "prompt": "What are some good probiotic foods I should add to my diet?",
  "response": "Incorporating probiotic-rich foods into your diet can support gut health and overall well-being. Here are some excellent options:\n\n1. **Yogurt**: Look for yogurt with live and active cultures. Greek yogurt is a great choice as it is also high in protein.\n\n2. **Kefir**: This fermented milk drink is rich in probiotics and can be consumed as a beverage or used in smoothies.\n\n3. **Sauerkraut**: Fermented cabbage that is high in probiotics and also contains vitamins C and K.\n\n4. **Kimchi**: A spicy Korean side dish made from fermented vegetables, usually cabbage and radishes, and is rich in probiotics.\n\n5. **Miso**: A Japanese seasoning made from fermented soybeans that can be used in soups, sauces, and dressings.\n\n6. **Tempeh**: A fermented soybean product that is high in protein and can be used in various dishes.\n\n7. **Pickles**: Fermented pickles (not just brined in vinegar) can be a good source of probiotics. Look for those made naturally with salt and water.\n\n8. **Kombucha**: A fermented tea beverage that is slightly effervescent and packed with probiotics.\n\n9. **Nattoo**: A traditional Japanese food made from fermented soybeans, known for its strong flavor and stickiness, and rich in probiotics and nutrients.\n\n10. **Fermented cheeses**: Some cheeses, such as Gouda, cheddar, and swiss, contain probiotics, particularly those that are aged.\n\nIncluding a variety of these foods in your diet can help enhance your gut flora and support digestion. Just be sure to choose products that specifically state they contain live cultures, and consider any dietary restrictions you may have.",
